depends on how much stock do our distributors hold, and how much, of course, they are going

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:05.119
to sell.

00:06:05.119 --> 00:06:09.839
So we need to look at how much they have in stock locally, how much they are going to

00:06:09.839 --> 00:06:17.320
sell, and based on this, we can estimate how much we are going to sell to the distributor,

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:23.519
and it will help us to know whether we are going to reach our yearly sales target, our

00:06:23.519 --> 00:06:24.519
budget.

00:06:24.519 --> 00:06:30.679
And eventually, if we are sure to reach it, or if we are able to reach it, we can decide

00:06:30.679 --> 00:06:35.399
to postpone or advance some supplies, which are going to invoice.

00:06:35.399 --> 00:06:41.239
So it becomes a kind of business tool, and sometimes also we are late to supply.

00:06:41.239 --> 00:06:45.359
So what you want to know is, is there any risk of shortage locally, if you are late

00:06:45.359 --> 00:06:51.359
of two weeks, one month, three months, can you run some simulation, if we supplied less

00:06:51.359 --> 00:06:58.559
than what was in pre-order, what are the consequences?

00:06:58.559 --> 00:07:01.440
Sometimes also we might have some supply constraints.

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:08.320
One product can be used by several countries, and we need to manage some allocations, giving

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:14.299
some stock to some distributors to maybe cover the next four weeks, six weeks.

00:07:14.299 --> 00:07:22.239
So having a view on the projected inventories will help to manage this type of situation.

00:07:22.239 --> 00:07:26.440
So this was what was needed for the business.

00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:34.880
And from a supply chain point of view, all this can be summarized into two points, how

00:07:34.880 --> 00:07:42.000
can we get a shared visibility of the stocks at our distributor level, of their local projected

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:46.519
inventories, and calculate together a replenishment plan.

00:07:46.519 --> 00:07:53.320
And ideally, we would like to have an app which is simple to use and available quickly.

00:07:53.320 --> 00:07:57.720
It could be made maybe in a couple of days.

00:07:57.720 --> 00:08:03.200
And we are not connected to our distributors, so all this will be about processing some

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:07.920
data in Excel and CSV files.

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:13.079
So today, or before, how does it look like when we work with our distributors?

00:08:13.079 --> 00:08:19.559
If you work on Excel, you can have some massive Excel file, a little bit scary when you open

00:08:19.559 --> 00:08:20.559
them.

00:08:20.799 --> 00:08:26.200
There are plenty of lines, and sometimes plenty of comments, and plenty of formulas.

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:30.320
So most of the time, it looks like this sample.

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:39.320
We have in the first column, the code, the description, and after we have the sales forecast,

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:44.440
so what the distributor is going to sell, their stock, opening inventories, at their

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:49.159
local distribution center, some goods in transit, based on this, we are going to calculate some

00:08:49.159 --> 00:08:57.000
projected inventories, in units, in coverage, and a supply plan.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:02.280
So when you have this, you can see here it's only for one product, you have 5 or 10 lines,

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:07.880
so imagine when you have 100 products, it becomes really big, and it's a little bit

00:09:07.880 --> 00:09:16.679
difficult to read, because each distributor might have its own format, so it becomes massive,

00:09:16.679 --> 00:09:21.280
and many formulas mean so many errors.

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:26.320
So the idea was to check, can we do something in R, and actually when you look a little

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:32.280
bit further, we have some yellow colors here, it's always the same thing that we see, it's

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:36.919
a demand, sales forecast, the product inventories, and a supply plan.

00:09:36.919 --> 00:09:39.000
So basically we have three vectors.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:45.320
So we say vectors might say R, so R might be a good fit for it.

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:52.440
So it was then in 2017, the idea was, can we use R to perform those calculations, because

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:55.200
at the end you are just dealing with some vectors.

00:09:55.200 --> 00:10:04.400
So we created a program in R, so it was pretty quick to do, and in only a couple of days,

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:09.679
and in this program we do some calculations, which are related to a few columns, which

00:10:09.679 --> 00:10:16.960
are here, the period of time we can project ourselves a different level of granularity

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:22.880
per month, per week, per day, then you have a demand, it can be sales forecast, it can

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:29.000
be also some replenishment forecast out from the distributor to sub-distributors or partners,

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:33.880
in a range of projected inventories, in units, and in coverage, then a supply plan, which

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:41.080
is what is expected to arrive at our partners, and then you calculate also what you call

00:10:41.080 --> 00:10:47.080
a DRP, a distribution requirement planning, which is basically a supply plan, based on

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:48.080
some parameters.

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:52.080
So how does it work?

00:10:52.080 --> 00:11:01.559
So basically we get some raw data, about 10 files, several CSV files, which are related

00:11:01.559 --> 00:11:08.000
to the sales out of the distributors, their actual sales out, their sales out forecast,

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:14.000
some data related to the sales in, the actual sales in, so what we sold to them in the last

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:18.719
few months, some sales in forecast, what we plan to sell to them, then an expected

00:11:18.719 --> 00:11:23.440
supply plan, which is what we plan to sell to them or supply to them, which might be

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:30.599
aligned to the sales in forecast or different, some DRP parameters, we go through it a little

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:31.640
bit further.

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:37.239
Some opening inventories, which can be at the local distribution center or in transit,

00:11:37.239 --> 00:11:41.960
and what is also interesting for the business is to compare with some financial forecast,

00:11:41.960 --> 00:11:48.880
a budget, and another parameter is called a DRP grid, then a frozen horizon, that we

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:53.440
are going to look at more details a little bit further.

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:57.719
So 10 files that you are going to process.

00:11:57.719 --> 00:12:03.679
So to process them, we work with RStudio, so RStudio Desktop or RConnect.

00:12:03.679 --> 00:12:10.599
We perform all VTL, and after we get a result that we show in, or that we display in Shiny.

00:12:10.599 --> 00:12:11.599
Why using Shiny?

00:12:11.599 --> 00:12:18.719
Before I was, in 2017, using Qlik, QlikView, but actually Shiny is much, much easier when

00:12:18.719 --> 00:12:24.400
it comes to create some complex visualizations, especially when sometimes we need to aggregate

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:29.440
some data, take this result, and combine it with another aggregation.

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:35.280
So in Qlik, it was very complex to do, and in Shiny, it's just super easy.

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:40.520
After in Shiny, we have this part that you can call write-back capabilities, sometimes

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:47.760
using RnSumTable, it's very nice to type, to enter some data, and to learn some of our

00:12:47.799 --> 00:12:48.799
capabilities.

00:12:48.799 --> 00:12:54.679
What I like is the full control of the navigation, especially using the conditional panels,

00:12:54.679 --> 00:12:59.119
so it makes everything easier, and especially it's quick to duplicate.

00:12:59.119 --> 00:13:06.559
We see later after we can assemble, like assembling a puzzle, we have one app, another level,

00:13:06.559 --> 00:13:12.599
and we can assemble them together, and it's super fast using Shiny.

00:13:12.599 --> 00:13:15.760
So we talk about some calculations.

00:13:16.760 --> 00:13:23.760
So the first calculation is a very basic one called a projected inventory, so how does

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:24.760
it work?

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:29.239
Basically, on one product in one country, for example, we have 1,000 units.

00:13:29.239 --> 00:13:35.599
We are going to sell, in a current event, some quantities, and after we have a projected

00:13:35.599 --> 00:13:37.400
inventory, it's in supply.

00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:43.280
So 1,000 minus what you are going to sell this month, minus 100, it remains 900, minus

00:13:43.679 --> 00:13:51.320
100 the following month, it remains 800, minus 100 after it remains 700, plus the supply

00:13:51.320 --> 00:13:57.760
which is coming, so it becomes 7 plus 4, so 1,100, and so on.

00:13:57.760 --> 00:14:03.599
So we do this type of calculation, combining the different set of data, and we do it for

00:14:03.599 --> 00:14:08.640
all the product, whether there are 10 or thousands.

00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:13.559
The second calculation is a projected coverage.

00:14:13.559 --> 00:14:19.520
So basically, to illustrate it today, for example, we have 1,000 units in stock.

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:28.080
We are going to sell 200 units this month, 200 units next month, so 1,000 minus 600,

00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:35.559
it remains 400, and after, in two months from now, we are going to sell 800, and we have

00:14:35.559 --> 00:14:40.919
only 400, so we can cover two months and a half of demand.

00:14:40.919 --> 00:14:46.479
So to calculate the projected coverage, we need to look at how much we have in stock

00:14:46.479 --> 00:14:52.400
every month of the projected inventories, and we need to consume this stock based on

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:56.000
the coming sales forecast.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:04.840
So this type of formulae in Excel can be really massive, a lot of lines in each cell, so it

00:15:05.119 --> 00:15:10.559
becomes a very, very big file, and we might also create some errors when we do it, so

00:15:10.559 --> 00:15:11.559
it's not easy.

00:15:11.559 --> 00:15:18.320
So it's why some people also take a kind of shortcut, looking at the average last three,

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:22.960
six, 12 months of sales, or the next three, six, 12 months of sales.

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:28.080
It works, but sometimes if you have a strong seasonality or a strong trend, sales are decreasing

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:31.599
or increasing, it can lead to some mistake.

00:15:31.599 --> 00:15:41.799
So calculating this is very easy in R, following the first approach.

00:15:41.799 --> 00:15:44.840
Then we need to calculate a replenishment plan.

00:15:44.840 --> 00:15:49.159
So there are two popular options.

00:15:49.159 --> 00:15:55.359
The first one is using a fixed threshold, a fixed min and a fixed max, means every time

00:15:55.359 --> 00:16:02.039
our projected inventories go, decrease, or consume, and reach a minimum stock target,

00:16:02.039 --> 00:16:03.039
we replenish.

00:16:03.039 --> 00:16:06.200
And after we go down, we replenish.

00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:13.200
And in the first option here, which is a fixed threshold, we replenish every time we go,

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:20.400
for example, below 2,000 units, and replenish to be up to a max, which is 4.5 thousand units.

00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:29.039
Another way to calculate this replenishment plan is using a dynamic min and max that we

00:16:29.039 --> 00:16:35.559
can calculate based on the demand, on the forecast, saying, for example, that you want

00:16:35.559 --> 00:16:41.000
two months of coverage for a min, for example, and four months for a max.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:48.200
So if the sales are increasing, decreasing, or with seasonality, all is going to be automatically

00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:50.880
calculated and adjusted.

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:59.559
So this is the by default method that you are going to put in this app.

00:16:59.559 --> 00:17:04.160
And here, for example, if you define a min of two months and a max of four months, it

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:08.959
will mean that every two months, 4 minus 2, we are going to replenish.

00:17:08.959 --> 00:17:14.199
If you put a min of two months and a max of six months, it means we are going to replenish

00:17:14.199 --> 00:17:17.239
every four months, 6 minus 2.

00:17:17.239 --> 00:17:26.000
Then we have also some DRP parameters to calculate the replenishment quantity.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:33.920
So sometimes you want to replenish single boxes, or parcels, or pallets.

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:40.079
If you want to make the preparation time easier and the volumes are consequent, you might

00:17:40.079 --> 00:17:41.640
want to order some parcels.

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:45.239
It will be faster to perform the picking, or some pallets.

00:17:45.239 --> 00:17:50.719
If the volumes are big, it's much easier at the warehouse to handle the demand.

00:17:50.719 --> 00:17:59.079
So this app must be able to be customized based on the reorder quantities that you want

00:17:59.079 --> 00:18:04.400
to define per product.

00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:07.119
Another parameter is a frozen horizon.

00:18:07.160 --> 00:18:13.239
So we are going to receive from our distributors some purchase orders and some forecasts of

00:18:13.239 --> 00:18:14.239
supply.

00:18:14.239 --> 00:18:18.719
The idea is that in a frozen horizon, which can be the next three months, or the next

00:18:18.719 --> 00:18:24.439
six months, or maybe only one month, we only keep some purchase orders.

00:18:24.439 --> 00:18:29.839
And after, we have a kind of free horizon where we are going to launch a new calculation

00:18:29.839 --> 00:18:32.560
of DRP.

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:39.079
So this is a parameter that should be useful in the app to decide when we start replenishing

00:18:39.079 --> 00:18:45.560
and when we need to consider the existing POS, purchase orders, in our plan.

00:18:45.560 --> 00:18:49.040
But it's also useful if we need to manage some allocations.

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:53.520
For example, if we know that we have some supply constraints for the next four months,

00:18:53.520 --> 00:19:01.319
six months, and we cannot supply the level which would be calculated by DRP, we need

00:19:01.319 --> 00:19:03.000
to constrain the supply.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:07.280
So we can decide for some products or some countries to extend a frozen horizon and to

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:17.640
define what we need to, what you want to supply to everybody in those months.

00:19:17.640 --> 00:19:22.959
And the last one is a shipment date from the supplier.

00:19:22.959 --> 00:19:29.359
For example, we are going to calculate first when we need to receive our products in Indonesia

00:19:29.400 --> 00:19:32.719
or in Malaysia, and what products need to be shipped.

00:19:32.719 --> 00:19:38.959
They need to be shipped maybe 10 days earlier, maybe 20 or maybe 60 days earlier.

00:19:38.959 --> 00:19:49.599
All this depends on the delivery time, means how long between the supplier to the customer,

00:19:49.599 --> 00:19:53.800
considering the different means of transportation.

00:19:53.800 --> 00:20:00.000
We can ship by air, by sea, by truck, and we need to handle some product, we need to

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.640
do some local custom clearance.

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:06.359
So this can be put into parameters in the app.

00:20:06.359 --> 00:20:14.199
And sometimes also, some distributors may get invoice when we ship the product, or sometimes

00:20:14.199 --> 00:20:16.520
also when they receive the product.

00:20:16.520 --> 00:20:26.000
So for the sales and marketing team, it might be useful to have this information.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:33.640
So in summary, this app, or the R Markdown script, must calculate projected deliveries,

00:20:33.640 --> 00:20:40.040
projected coverages, replenishment plan, considering two parameters, a reorder quantity, a multiple

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:45.920
of it, a frozen period, and the last thing we need to calculate is a shipment date from

00:20:45.920 --> 00:20:49.000
the supplier, considering the delivery time.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:55.160
And those parameters, reorder quantity, frozen period, delivery time, must be customizable

00:20:55.160 --> 00:21:00.959
for each product, whether you use 10 products or 10,000.

00:21:00.959 --> 00:21:05.239
And the good news is that in R, it's super easy.

00:21:05.239 --> 00:21:09.599
Here it's a R Markdown file which is going to do all this calculation, there are only

00:21:09.599 --> 00:21:15.000
800 lines, actually most of the lines were spaces and commands.

00:21:15.079 --> 00:21:22.359
So it's a very short program to perform all this.

00:21:22.359 --> 00:21:29.319
And where are the people using this app?

00:21:29.319 --> 00:21:35.760
So there are four departments, so the first one is sales and marketing team, they want

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:42.719
to know how much we are going to sell this year or following year.

00:21:42.719 --> 00:21:49.239
The supply chain team of the company, and for the distributors, the controlling finance,

00:21:49.239 --> 00:21:55.880
they want to know also where we stand versus budget, and the country managers of each country

00:21:55.880 --> 00:21:59.319
or region.

00:21:59.319 --> 00:22:00.319
And what were the results?

00:22:00.319 --> 00:22:05.760
First, from reactivity, I would say we moved to productivity.

00:22:05.760 --> 00:22:10.800
Sometimes you had some supply issues, we need to deliver fast.

00:22:10.880 --> 00:22:16.520
It was very often due to, I would say, wrong planning.

00:22:16.520 --> 00:22:22.160
And if we don't look at the stock, at the distributors, we don't anticipate, we just

00:22:22.160 --> 00:22:24.359
see the problem right now.

00:22:24.359 --> 00:22:29.400
And by looking at the projected inventories, we really can see the potential problem in

00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:32.079
the next 6 or 12 months.

00:22:32.079 --> 00:22:35.599
We also avoid many mistakes due to calculations.

00:22:35.599 --> 00:22:40.079
When you look at the different Excel files that you receive from the distributors, for

00:22:40.359 --> 00:22:43.439
example, there was an issue due to the reasons that we mentioned earlier.

00:22:43.439 --> 00:22:48.599
Sometimes there were many, many formulas and they were just not correct.

00:22:48.599 --> 00:22:53.839
So we share visibility and we developed some partnership together.

00:22:53.839 --> 00:22:56.280
And we automated and simplified everything.

00:22:56.280 --> 00:23:04.560
As we saw before, it's a very short RMADOM file, not even 800 lines, so it's very quick

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:08.239
to code all this.

00:23:08.239 --> 00:23:11.359
And it allows us not to have any more functions.

00:23:11.359 --> 00:23:16.280
We keep the databases very clean, the 10 files that we saw before.

00:23:16.280 --> 00:23:21.719
And obviously, we save a lot of time for everybody at the distributor level or at the company

00:23:21.719 --> 00:23:22.719
level.

00:23:22.719 --> 00:23:24.880
And you can focus on analysis.

00:23:24.880 --> 00:23:32.400
And what is nice is that what is good in one region, so we are talking about here Sophistasia,

00:23:32.400 --> 00:23:36.959
is that it's easily duplicable in other parts of the world.

00:23:36.959 --> 00:23:41.040
We have some distributors in the Middle East, in Central America.

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:43.239
It's the same code, it's the same app.

