00:25:46.839 --> 00:25:51.839
So here, every two months, we replace some quantities.

00:25:51.839 --> 00:25:57.839
And basically, at the beginning, we have only here a minimum stock,

00:25:57.839 --> 00:26:00.839
which is equivalent to three months of sales,

00:26:00.839 --> 00:26:04.839
which is increasing and changing depending on the month.

00:26:04.839 --> 00:26:08.839
The maximum stock in the middle, in yellow.

00:26:08.839 --> 00:26:12.839
We have our projected inventories, which is always between min and max,

00:26:12.839 --> 00:26:18.839
calculated based on the supply plan here on the right.

00:26:18.839 --> 00:26:21.839
And here on the top, we have our parameters.

00:26:21.839 --> 00:26:24.839
So how does it work?

00:26:24.839 --> 00:26:29.839
We have some parameters, a frozen horizon.

00:26:29.839 --> 00:26:31.839
This is what we saw before.

00:26:31.839 --> 00:26:33.839
So we can customize it per product.

00:26:33.839 --> 00:26:37.839
So product A has a frozen horizon only in January.

00:26:37.839 --> 00:26:39.839
And after it's free, we can calculate the DRP.

00:26:39.839 --> 00:26:43.839
Product B is frozen until March.

00:26:43.839 --> 00:26:52.839
So if you look at product B, we can see that the DRP is going to start only in April.

00:26:52.839 --> 00:26:57.839
After we have, in this frozen horizon, some PO, existing purchase orders,

00:26:57.839 --> 00:27:04.839
that we are going to upload and to keep in the frozen horizon as a confirmed supply plan.

00:27:05.839 --> 00:27:12.839
And in this simple app, we have a simulation to see how does it look like.

00:27:12.839 --> 00:27:16.839
So we have four products.

00:27:16.839 --> 00:27:22.839
And here on the left, we have different parameters just to illustrate how it works.

00:27:22.839 --> 00:27:26.839
So here we have a safety stock of three months.

00:27:26.839 --> 00:27:32.839
It means we want to keep always three months and a frequency of supply of four months.

00:27:32.839 --> 00:27:35.839
So a maximum stock of three plus four, seven.

00:27:35.839 --> 00:27:40.839
You can see that our coverage here is always between three and seven.

00:27:40.839 --> 00:27:44.839
We can change it, we can put a safety stock of two months.

00:27:44.839 --> 00:27:49.839
Our coverage changes, we are between two and six.

00:27:49.839 --> 00:27:54.839
We can put a frequency of supply every two months.

00:27:54.839 --> 00:27:57.839
We are always between two and five.

00:27:57.839 --> 00:28:03.839
And we replenish every two months or we can change it and make it like this every five months.

00:28:03.839 --> 00:28:13.839
So what we do here on the simple example, we are going to later to do it on a hundred or even thousand of product.

00:28:13.839 --> 00:28:17.839
We have a survey order quantity, here is a multiple of one.

00:28:17.839 --> 00:28:21.839
We can put maybe one hundred.

00:28:22.839 --> 00:28:27.839
And we have our calculated DRP, which is going to take multiple of hundred.

00:28:27.839 --> 00:28:33.839
There is a frozen period here, which runs until February.

00:28:33.839 --> 00:28:37.839
We can put it until May.

00:28:37.839 --> 00:28:46.839
And you can see that our DRP is only going to start replenishing from May.

00:28:46.839 --> 00:28:53.839
And if you make it later, maybe in July, it will start calculating in July.

00:28:53.839 --> 00:28:57.839
And you will see that we are too late, we are going to be in shortage.

00:28:57.839 --> 00:29:01.839
Our coverage is negative as well as the projected inventories here.

00:29:01.839 --> 00:29:07.839
And we have another parameter, this one, DLT, delivery time.

00:29:07.839 --> 00:29:09.839
So what does it look like?

00:29:09.839 --> 00:29:12.839
We have what you can call a market date and a plan date.

00:29:13.839 --> 00:29:22.839
For example, here in July, we want to receive locally 7,400 units.

00:29:22.839 --> 00:29:29.839
If we need only 15 days to get those products, it means they need to be shipped, let's say, one month earlier.

00:29:29.839 --> 00:29:32.839
Supposing you want them at the very first of the month.

00:29:32.839 --> 00:29:41.839
And if you have 60 days of delivery time, the same quantity needs to be shipped two months earlier.

00:29:42.839 --> 00:29:50.839
So those 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 parameters are the ones that we are going to use in our demand and supply planning.

