Bangladesh, Cambodia, Indonesia, Malaysia, and so on.

00:30:58.839 --> 00:31:06.839
So in those countries, or to those countries, we supply some products from one supplier.

00:31:06.839 --> 00:31:10.839
So we maybe select only up to two families of product.

00:31:10.839 --> 00:31:19.839
Each family of product can have a sub-product into it, which are going to different countries.

00:31:19.839 --> 00:31:27.839
So the idea here is, imagine that you are in the region, you are in the business, and you are in charge of all those countries.

00:31:28.839 --> 00:31:30.839
You want to know a few things.

00:31:30.839 --> 00:31:35.839
You want to know, out of your distributors, how things are going.

00:31:35.839 --> 00:31:42.839
So we are going to look at maybe here one distributor, Malaysia.

00:31:42.839 --> 00:31:45.839
We are going to look at the sales out.

00:31:45.839 --> 00:31:52.839
Their family, or maybe I put all the families here, of their product.

00:31:52.839 --> 00:32:01.839
So we are in the business, we want to see the actual sales, what we sold out of the distributor, for one product or all the products,

00:32:01.839 --> 00:32:06.839
and the sales out forecast, what we are going to sell out of the distributor.

00:32:06.839 --> 00:32:15.839
And maybe there is a similarity, so you want to see it as a month-to-month chart.

00:32:15.839 --> 00:32:19.839
Or maybe there is a trend, so you may want to look at it this way.

00:32:20.839 --> 00:32:32.839
And it's also interesting to look at it in a consolidated way in a table, to see the growth or decrease, or stability per product.

00:32:32.839 --> 00:32:39.839
But at the end, what we are going to sell is here, sales in versus in.

00:32:39.839 --> 00:32:47.839
So based on the sales out, we are going to calculate replenishment plan, and this is what we are going to analyse here.

00:32:47.839 --> 00:32:51.839
How much we sold per product, how much we are going to sell.

00:32:51.839 --> 00:32:58.839
And all this is in units, it gives us a sense of what are the main products and where we go.

00:32:58.839 --> 00:33:01.839
But also we can valorise it.

00:33:01.839 --> 00:33:09.839
And here it comes, useful for the businesses, is this view, maybe I make it like that.

00:33:09.839 --> 00:33:15.839
Year-to-date versus last year-to-date, not in units as we saw before, but in euros.

00:33:15.839 --> 00:33:18.839
And we also can compare with the budget.

00:33:18.839 --> 00:33:25.839
So, what we sold in the last period per product, we are in Malaysia.

00:33:25.839 --> 00:33:29.839
What we sold now, we can see the variations, where we are going.

00:33:29.839 --> 00:33:42.839
And you can also project yourself for the whole fiscal year, or calendar year, and to see whether we have some upside-downside versus budget.

00:33:43.839 --> 00:33:47.839
And at the end, the question is, am I going to make my budget?

00:33:47.839 --> 00:33:51.839
Yes or no, do I have room to postpone some supplies?

00:33:51.839 --> 00:34:00.839
If I have insurance that I'm going to reach my target this year, maybe I want to keep some sales for next year.

00:34:00.839 --> 00:34:06.839
And if I have enough stock at the distributor level, maybe I can postpone some shipments or decrease them.

00:34:06.839 --> 00:34:13.840
So, it becomes a tool to help the business to achieve their target.

00:34:13.840 --> 00:34:17.840
Then you can look at the projected inventories at the distributor level.

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:21.840
So, we are in Malaysia, let's look at maybe this product, product 7.

00:34:26.840 --> 00:34:28.840
We can look at the projected inventories.

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:33.840
Today, we have locally about 27,000 units.

00:34:34.840 --> 00:34:41.840
There is something upcoming in June, about 10,000 units.

00:34:41.840 --> 00:34:43.840
So, we have 5 months of stock, so far so good.

00:34:43.840 --> 00:34:49.840
And we get you a DRP, which gives us a supply every 2 months.

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:53.840
Because we have a frequency of supply every 2 months here, so no problem.

00:34:53.840 --> 00:35:00.840
But we have a lot of products, and it might not be very easy to look at all those products one by one.

00:35:00.840 --> 00:35:04.840
Imagine that you have only here in Malaysia all this, about 60 products.

00:35:04.840 --> 00:35:10.840
So, not so comfortable to look at this view for all the products in all distributors.

00:35:10.840 --> 00:35:14.840
So, we can create what you can call here a supply risk alarm.

00:35:14.840 --> 00:35:16.840
We are going to select all our products.

00:35:16.840 --> 00:35:25.840
And we can look at the projected coverages in months, at the end of each month, per product.

00:35:25.840 --> 00:35:30.840
So, you can see whether there are some risks or not of supplies.

00:35:30.840 --> 00:35:45.840
So, for example, this one, product 31, is decreasing only a few months of coverage and shortage in July.

00:35:45.840 --> 00:35:47.840
So, let's look at it, 31.

00:35:52.840 --> 00:35:54.840
Actually, we are going to discontinue.

00:35:54.840 --> 00:35:57.840
So, we are going to receive something after not enough stock.

00:35:57.840 --> 00:36:00.840
And the DRP tells us we should get something else.

00:36:00.840 --> 00:36:05.840
So, we can use this view to look at the current coverages.

00:36:05.840 --> 00:36:11.840
But also to look at the result of all our calculations, the DRP, with the new coverages.

00:36:11.840 --> 00:36:20.840
So, we can see here that every 2 months or every 3 months, depending on the product, we replenish something.

00:36:21.840 --> 00:36:25.840
Sometimes it's fine, sometimes maybe a little bit too late.

00:36:25.840 --> 00:36:35.840
This one, number 44, maybe we need to advance our supply.

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:40.840
So, when you look at it, today we have 500 units in stock.

00:36:40.840 --> 00:36:41.840
We sell a bit.

00:36:41.840 --> 00:36:44.840
We are very low, less than 2 months of stock.

00:36:44.840 --> 00:36:47.840
And the next supply will be this one in August.

00:36:47.840 --> 00:36:48.840
It's too late.

00:36:48.840 --> 00:36:57.840
Maybe we might want to check with our factory whether we can supply earlier, maybe totally or partially from it.

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:10.840
And what is also interesting is that here, when you see all the products, we saw that we have some risk of shortages or maybe also some risk of overstocks.

00:37:10.840 --> 00:37:14.840
And we might have several pages.

00:37:14.840 --> 00:37:20.840
Here, there are not so many, only 3 pages, but sometimes it can be thousands of products.

00:37:20.840 --> 00:37:28.840
And it's where R becomes very, very useful to do this part, what you can call prescriptive analytics.

00:37:28.840 --> 00:37:38.840
So, basically, we can create a program which is going to screen all those lines and to analyze for us whether there is a risk of shortage or overstock.

00:37:38.840 --> 00:37:47.840
And also quantify the impact in terms of sales, maybe missing sales, in terms of cash flow, if you have too much stock.

00:37:47.840 --> 00:37:50.840
And propose us some possible scenarios.

00:37:50.840 --> 00:37:57.840
For example, if one product, if you go back to the flows here, maybe I take one product, maybe two.

00:37:57.840 --> 00:38:00.840
And I take everybody.

00:38:00.840 --> 00:38:05.840
Or maybe product 14.

00:38:05.840 --> 00:38:08.840
For example, this one.

00:38:08.840 --> 00:38:13.840
So, this product is sold in Malaysia, in Indonesia, in Singapore, Vietnam, and so on.

00:38:13.840 --> 00:38:22.840
So, if one country has a risk of shortage, maybe another one can help to ship some product.

00:38:22.840 --> 00:38:29.840
So, you can see here the volume for this area, from Bangladesh, from Cambodia, Malaysia, and so on.

00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:32.840
Maybe some countries can help another one.

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:34.840
And all this can be coded.

00:38:34.840 --> 00:38:40.840
So, we can create our scenarios in the algorithm.

00:38:40.840 --> 00:38:46.840
And RLF is going to screen all this and to propose us some solutions.

00:38:46.840 --> 00:38:50.840
So, this can be very nice.

