Perfect.

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:47.840
So, now I'm going to show you with less detail.

00:41:47.840 --> 00:41:50.840
Some other examples that we can do.

00:41:50.840 --> 00:41:53.840
It's always the same approach.

00:41:53.840 --> 00:41:59.840
To show you how this code is scalable and reproducible.

00:41:59.840 --> 00:42:06.840
So, in this, we are using the products that you are using in the division I'm working with.

00:42:06.840 --> 00:42:08.840
So, intraocular analysis.

00:42:08.840 --> 00:42:10.840
It's just like glasses.

00:42:10.840 --> 00:42:13.840
You have different degrees.

00:42:13.840 --> 00:42:16.840
So, one product.

00:42:17.840 --> 00:42:27.840
Or one product family comes into maybe 30 or 50 types of degrees.

00:42:27.840 --> 00:42:30.840
And even more, if you are using what you call toric lenses.

00:42:30.840 --> 00:42:37.840
So, you have not only a power, but also a cylinder.

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:45.840
So, in this, a special manager in one country will manage maybe 10 or 15 product families.

00:42:45.840 --> 00:42:49.840
But in terms of queue, it's huge.

00:42:49.840 --> 00:42:54.840
It can be 1 or 2,000 materials to manage.

00:42:54.840 --> 00:42:59.840
And when it comes to demand and supply planning, so all we use Excel.

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:04.840
And you can imagine that with this portfolio, it becomes really, really tough.

00:43:04.840 --> 00:43:06.840
Or you use R.

00:43:06.840 --> 00:43:08.840
And it becomes very simple.

00:43:08.840 --> 00:43:12.840
And in some countries, we are using R.

00:43:13.840 --> 00:43:19.840
And it's really easy to go a little bit further.

00:43:19.840 --> 00:43:25.840
For example, in the example that we saw before, we are looking at projected inventories at monthly bucket.

00:43:25.840 --> 00:43:29.840
And here, we are going to look at the same thing.

00:43:29.840 --> 00:43:31.840
So, projected inventories per week.

00:43:31.840 --> 00:43:37.840
So, we can split our monthly sales forecast that we do in R or another tool.

00:43:37.840 --> 00:43:41.840
We are going to split this monthly sales forecast into weekly sales forecast.

00:43:41.840 --> 00:43:44.840
And we even can consider different type of things.

00:43:44.840 --> 00:43:45.840
We can consider L pattern.

00:43:45.840 --> 00:43:49.840
For example, we sell all the products the first week of the month and after less.

00:43:49.840 --> 00:43:50.840
Or a G pattern.

00:43:50.840 --> 00:43:52.840
We sell everything the last week of the month.

00:43:52.840 --> 00:43:54.840
Or a regular pattern.

00:43:54.840 --> 00:43:57.840
We sell roughly the same quantity every week.

00:43:57.840 --> 00:44:02.840
And we got our monthly sales forecast split into weekly sales forecast.

00:44:02.840 --> 00:44:08.840
And after, we are going to distribute our sales forecast per diopter or diopter cylinder.

00:44:08.840 --> 00:44:10.840
So, all this calculation is done in R.

00:44:10.840 --> 00:44:18.840
We get after a different set of demand, which are actually weekly sales forecast at skew, at material level.

00:44:18.840 --> 00:44:21.840
So, it's about millions of rows to process.

00:44:21.840 --> 00:44:26.840
And this is done very, very easily in R with the same code that we saw before.

00:44:26.840 --> 00:44:29.840
And after, we just look at it in Shiny.

00:44:29.840 --> 00:44:37.840
Another example is this one or the next one.

00:44:37.840 --> 00:44:40.840
We are talking before about a single level DRP.

00:44:40.840 --> 00:44:43.840
Now, we are going to look at multiple level DRP.

00:44:43.840 --> 00:44:57.840
And we said that R is very easy to become scalable and reproducible because the same code that we are going to duplicate depending on the different levels where we are.

00:44:57.840 --> 00:45:03.840
For example, here, we have a factory shipping some product to a regional hub.

00:45:03.840 --> 00:45:10.840
Shipping some product, the same product, after maybe some repacking to different countries.

00:45:10.840 --> 00:45:13.840
Here, Singapore, Philippines, Malaysia and so on, Thailand.

00:45:13.840 --> 00:45:17.840
And those countries have a local stock that they are going to ship to their customers.

00:45:17.840 --> 00:45:24.840
So, what we are going to do is to calculate first the DRP replenishment plan here at the country level.

00:45:24.840 --> 00:45:26.840
In Malaysia, in Thailand, so on.

00:45:26.840 --> 00:45:33.840
We are going to get the result of this DRP and to use it at demand for the regional hub.

00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:35.840
And then, at the regional hub, we have to keep some stock.

00:45:35.840 --> 00:45:41.840
So, we calculate another DRP and we get the replenishment plan from the factory to the regional hub.

00:45:41.840 --> 00:45:53.840
So, in R, we can calculate the whole flow from the market to the factory modeling this network.

00:45:53.840 --> 00:45:56.840
It's just the same code that we copy-paste two times.

00:45:56.840 --> 00:46:00.840
So, it's really simple and really quick.

00:46:00.840 --> 00:46:09.840
And in ZEISS, we are also using Shiny to animate our SNOP sales and operation planning process every month.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:17.840
So, I couldn't put the flow of ZEISS, but here I put something very similar.

00:46:18.840 --> 00:46:24.840
So, imagine that you are in Spain, you have a factory in Madrid, you ship to a global hub in Barcelona.

00:46:24.840 --> 00:46:29.840
And from there, you ship your product to some affiliates, to some dealers, distributors.

00:46:29.840 --> 00:46:35.840
Or maybe also to a regional hub and from a regional hub to the different countries.

00:46:35.840 --> 00:46:43.840
So, following the same approach that we saw until now, we can calculate the replenishment plan of each entity here.

00:46:44.840 --> 00:46:49.840
And we get this result to know how much the global hub needs to ship.

00:46:49.840 --> 00:46:59.840
And then we recalculate again the DRP eventually here to see how much the factory needs to supply to the global hub.

00:46:59.840 --> 00:47:05.840
And when you have the factory, we can model how much we need to produce versus the production capacities,

00:47:05.840 --> 00:47:10.840
a min, a max, to see where we are and whether everything goes well.

00:47:10.840 --> 00:47:19.840
Or if we foresee in the next 18 or 24 months, a decrease of charge or maybe too much demand.

00:47:19.840 --> 00:47:25.840
Maybe we need then to make some adjustments in our production plan to adapt.

00:47:26.840 --> 00:47:28.840
And we also can play on some parameters.

00:47:28.840 --> 00:47:37.840
We also can play on the safety stock, DLT, delivery time to run some scenarios if needed.

00:47:37.840 --> 00:47:46.840
And we also can constrain the sales if we need to work on some allocations.

